tOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlasma albumin\u003C/strong\u003E is the main determinant of oncotic pressure due to its high concentration and molecular weight. Albumin accounts for approximately 80% of the total plasma oncotic pressure, with other plasma proteins contributing the remainder.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlasma potassium\u003C/strong\u003E - Potassium ions are too small and readily cross capillary membranes, thus do not generate oncotic pressure\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlasma bicarbonate\u003C/strong\u003E - While important for acid-base balance, bicarbonate freely crosses capillary membranes and does not contribute significantly to oncotic pressure\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlasma calcium\u003C/strong\u003E - Calcium ions are too small to contribute meaningfully to oncotic pressure\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlasma glucose\u003C/strong\u003E - Glucose molecules are too small to generate significant oncotic pressure\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EA reduction in plasma albumin (hypoalbuminaemia) leads to decreased oncotic pressure and can result in oedema as fluid shifts from the intravascular to the interstitial space.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Oncotic pressure is primarily determined by plasma proteins, especially albumin which contributes about 80% of the total effect.","Oncotic pressure is essential for maintaining fluid balance between intravascular and interstitial compartments."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRev